node.text: The 2021 Apple iMac is an all-in-one desktop that is powerful, yet pretty. It's lightweight and colorful, and once you plug it in you are ready to go.  However, some quirky annoyances and a few needed upgrades will add some extra dollar signs to the price tag. WIRED's @julianchokkattu has more details about the completely redesigned iMac. Tap the link in our bio to read the full review.

node.title: Apple's Colorful New iMac Pairs Beauty With Brawn

Across 15 eastern states, the same ritual is underway. Billions of cicadas are emerging this week from Brood X—a population of three separate species (two from the genus Magicicada) that emerge from the ground at the same time. There are a dozen broods of 17-year cicadas and three broods of 13-year cicadas in the eastern US, each appearing in different years. But why are #cicadas so freakin' loud? Entomologist Samuel Ramsey has the answers.

Watch the full video at www.youtube.com/WIRED

node.text:
Having slow internet is the worrrrst. And while it might not be your router's fault, there are lots of easy ways to make sure the problem isn't at home. Here are some easy ways to upgrade your speeds, with more tips at the link in the bio. 

🎨: @elacey_creative

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by WIRED on August 18, 2021. May be an image of text that says '5 WAYS TO UPGRADE YOUR HOME WI-FI Increasing your internet speed is easier than you might think. Here's how to do it right >>>'.

Photo by WIRED on August 18, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'MOVE YOUR ROUTER Router stuffed away in a closet? Doors and walls can dampen your signal, so try to have your router as close to your devices as you can with as few obstacles as possible. If you don't have a flat surface where you want it, try mounting it on the wall.'.

Photo by WIRED on August 18, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'CHANGE THE CHANNEL OR BAND Your signal is divided into channels, and if your Wi-Fi channel is too close to a neighbor's it can get congested quickly. Your router's instructions should tell you how to switch to a different channel to see if that's happening to you.'.

Photo by WIRED on August 18, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'CUTOFE UNUSED DEVICES Once your neighbors are off, it's time to kick off those gadgets that still take up internet when you're not using them. Most good routers will let you prioritize and cut off certain devices.'.

Photo by WIRED on August 18, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'PASSWORD YOUR WI-FI The more devices using your router, the slower your internet will be. So protect your Wi-Fi from your neighbor's Netflix binge with a secure password. This helps with potential hacking, too.'.

Photo by WIRED on August 18, 2021. May be an image of text that says '1 !! GET A WI-FI EXTENDER If these other steps aren't enough, it's time to give in and purchase a Wi-Fi extender. These devices plug into a spare wall socket and can help eliminate deadzones in your house.'.
Photo by WIRED on August 18, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'FOR MORE INTERNET BOOSTING TIPS, HEAD TO THE LINK IN THE BIO.'.

node.text: Pour one out for Internet Explorer—the since-discontinued web browser that was born on this day in 1995. Internet Explorer was once the dominant web browser, winning the early battle against Netscape and attaining a peak of about 95% usage share by 2003. But then came Chrome, Firefox, and mobile browsers and well, the rest is history.

This timelapse of Shasta Lake in Northern California from @dailyoverview compares water levels in late June 2020 to a recent image in late May 2021. The surface elevation of the reservoir was at 1,016 feet in the first image and was already down to 959 feet at an earlier stage in the summer this year. This difference of 57 feet equates to a volume loss of more 359 billion gallons — enough water to fill an Olympic swimming pool 550,000 times. 
—

This image from inside the La Silla Observatory dome in the Chilean desert stares up into the stars, right at the center of our Milky Way galaxy. With its bright yellow center, the galactic core steals the show. The heart of our galaxy is home to dense and active star-forming regions—and also home to many black holes, though you can’t see them in this photo. See more beauties from worlds beyond at the link in the bio. 

📸: P. Horalek/ESO

node.text:
For the cover story of our current issue, Jason Parham tells the story of how a young app called Twitter—launched with the goal of changing how people communicate online—gave way to something bigger. With the birth of Black Twitter, it became a voice for the voiceless, creating one of the most dynamic subsets not only of Twitter but of the wider social internet—capable of creating, shaping, and remixing popular culture at lightspeed. Take in the very first chronicling of one of the internet's most powerful communities at the link in the bio.

🎨: Aaron Marin (@neutokyo)

node.text:
Although the world has changed considerably since woolly mammoths roamed the earth, the unique isotope ratios in Alaskan rocks and soil have more or less stayed the same. A new paper is the first to outline the entire life of a single wooly mammoth born over 17,000 years ago—all the way until its death by starvation. 

Read more about the mammoth's life story, and how the researchers discovered it, at the link in the bio.

node.text:
Hedgehogs may have looks to quill, but there's a dark side to the #hedgehoglife. While they do happen to be unbearably cute, the reality of owning one can be expensive and fraught. Like any exotic animal, many people don't know how to properly take care of them which leads to many hedgehogs ending up in the hands of rescuers, or dying prematurely.

Read more about the dark side of the #hedgehog social media craze at the link in the bio. 

📸: Shayan Asgharnia

node.text:
An alarming new report that includes 14,000 pieces of scientific literature paints a devastating picture of the path forward when it comes to climate change. It’s a full-throated declaration of what scientists know about how humanity has set the planet on fire: How hot it’s gotten and how hot it’s going to get, how much polar ice is melting, how droughts and storms are worsening, and how dire the path forward looks—unless we take drastic and immediate steps to stop loading the atmosphere with carbon. 

Read more about the findings of the report at the link in the bio.

node.text:
Every time you go online, the terms you search, the links you click on, and the decisions you make are being logged and tracked in all manner of ways. Here's how you can cover some of those tracks—and maybe even not leave any in the first place. Read more at the link in the bio. 

🎨: @elacey_creative

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by WIRED on August 09, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'I HOW TO COVER YOUR TRACKS EVERY TIME YOU GO ONLINE Online tracking can often feel downright invasive, but here are some steps to protect yourself'.

Photo by WIRED on August 09, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'GO INCOGNITO Most browsers have an Incognito or Private mode option for web browsing. It stops them from saving your search history and storing cookies on your device, but it doesn't stop your employer or internet service provider from seeing it. AI 1Ull// 1I'.

Photo by WIRED on August 09, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'USE A VPN What Incognito does for your device, VPN does for everyone else. It also allows you to pretend you're accessing the web from a different country which can come in handy, too.'.

Photo by WIRED on August 09, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'CLEAR YOUR BROWSING HISTORY If you haven't been using a VPN or a private mode, you may want to head into your browser and clear your history yourself. Keep in mind it may be on your machine, and in something like Google's cloud, but you can clear both.'.

Photo by WIRED on August 09, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'If that isn't enough, you take it a step further with browsers like Tor that are built for maximum protection, or even TailsOS, an operating system built around Tor. Head to the link in the bio for more tips on how to stay under the radar on the web.'.
